  "@ben_alman": "",
  "Facebook: Rethink established best practices™": "",
  "To answer that, we need to go back to before React was created.": "",
  "At the time, building for the web was... different. jQuery, Backbone, and Angular dominated discussion.": "",
  "jQuery was the most popular way to build for the web. It embraced websites for what they truly were, a tree of DOM nodes. With jQuery, the state of your application lived inside the DOM. Whenever you wanted to update that state, you'd imperatively traverse the DOM, find the node you wanted to update, then update it. Needed to respond to an event? Again, traverse the DOM, find the node, then add an event listener to it.": "",
  "bad idea": "",
  "Backbone.js invented the Model-View-Controller pattern. That's a joke, but it was the first popular JavaScript framework that embraced the traditional software design pattern and brought it to building for the web.": "",
  "In just 2,000 lines of code, Backbone allowed you to decouple your application's state from the DOM. Instead of living in the DOM, Backbone state lived inside of its \"Models\". From there, whenever a Model changed, all the Views that cared about that Model's state would re-render.": "",
  "That was it. Backbone's entire philosophy was to be as minimal and as unopinionated as possible. So much so, that the default implementation of Backbone's method responsible for rendering the View was a no-op. Meaning it was entirely up to you to implement your own View and templating strategy.": "",
  "source code": "",
  "But you know what wasn't minimal and unopinionated? Angular.js": "",
  "The idea was simple. What if HTML was... more powerful.": "",
  "Two way data binding": "",
  "data filters": "",
  "dependency injection": "",
  "mini version of jQuery": "",
  "Angular.js changed the game because it was a true, opinionated, all in one framework for building web applications.": "",
  "You need to remember the environment we were in here too. This was 2011. Being a pure \"Front end developer\" was much more uncommon than it is today. The highly opinionated nature of Angular.js was convenient for back-end developers who were given the unfortunate task of working on the front-end. This wasn't as uncommon as you might expect and it fueled Angular.js's popularity.": "",
  "The problem, among other things, was that Angular.js loved two-way data binding. It was Angular's way of updating the view whenever the model changed, and updating the model, whenever the view changed.": "",
  "Now, though they were the most popular, building for the web consisted of more than just jQuery, Backbone, and Angular. But regardless, the majority of these post jQuery frameworks had one thing in common, Models. These Models were essentially just observable objects that synced with the View - as we saw with Backbone, and in some cases - Views that could sync back with Models - as we saw with Angular.js.": "",
  "The problem was this pattern encouraged mutation, and naturally, mutation tends to increase complexity. But what if you could avoid this problem entirely? Now obviously you can't completely avoid mutations, but could you create an abstraction which minimized its negative effects?": "",
  "This is at the heart of what React tries to do.": "",
  "One of the core innovations of React was that they made the View a function of your application's State. Often represented as \u0000SKIP#138\u0000.": "",
  "All you have to do is worry about how the state in your application changes, and React handles the rest.": "",
  "But this was really only half the picture. The real innovation happened when you encapsulated this idea into a proper component based API. By doing so, the same intuition you have about creating and composing together functions can directly apply to creating and composing components. However, instead of composing functions together to get some value, you can compose components together to get some UI.": "",
  "To truly embrace a component based API, React needed a way to allow you to describe what the UI for a component would look like from inside the component itself. This is where most of the initial hate for React came from and it had to do with React's interpretation of the \"Separation of Concern's\" principle.": "",
  "If you're not familiar, \"Separation of Concerns\" is a software design principle for \"separating a computer program into distinct sections\". Historically the way you adhered to this on the web was to have your HTML separate from your CSS which was separate from your JavaScript.": "",
  "But React had a... different interpretation.": "",
  "In React's opinion, separating your HTML from your CSS from your JavaScript got you no where closer to true \"separation of concerns\". Instead, it was more just a separation of technology - which wasn't particularly valuable.": "",
  "In React's opinion, anything that had to do with rendering the View - whether that be state, UI, and in some cases, even styling, was part of its concern.": "",
  "To accomplish this, React needed a way to allow you to describe what the UI for a component would look like from inside the component itself. Well, describing UI is already a solved problem - that's what HTML is really good at. But you can't mix HTML and JavaScript, right?": "",
  "Why not?": "",
  "What made JSX different was it combined the power and expressiveness of JavaScript with the readability and accessibility of HTML. If you were already comfortable with both JavaScript and HTML (which you probably were, if you were building web apps), then you could get up to speed with JSX in a matter of minutes.": "",
  "Yes, it was weird, and different, and most people hated it at first, but once you used it in an actual app, it became clear that React was onto something with their interpretation of the Separation of Concerns principle.": "",
  "third party components": "",
  "So that was React in 2013. What's different today?": "",
  "From a philosophical perspective, honestly not much. You still create components which contain or receive everything they need to render the UI, then you compose those components together to get your application. Though the API for doing this has changed over the years as JavaScript has matured, fundamentally, things are still the same.": "",
